TY  - JOUR
T1  - Project Assignment Rights and Incentives for Eliciting Ideas
AU  - Arya, Anil
AU  - Glover, Jonathan
AU  - Routledge, Bryan R.
Y1  - 2002/07/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.48.7.886.2822
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.48.7.886.2822
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 886
EP  - 899
VL  - 48
IS  - 7
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In this paper, we study an incentive problem that arises between a principal and two agents because they value a real option differently. The real option in our model is a timing option. The agents have limited capacity to undertake projects, and each agent's capacity can be filled now or later. Because the principal cares about capacity in the aggregate but each agent cares only about his own capacity, the agents assign a higher value to the option to wait. As a result, agents sometimes withhold ideas from the principal. We show that decentralization can be a solution to this problem. Delegating assignment rights to an agent reduces the option value of waiting for the other agent sufficiently that he is willing to reveal his ideas.
AB  - In this paper, we study an incentive problem that arises between a principal and two agents because they value a real option differently. The real option in our model is a timing option. The agents have limited capacity to undertake projects, and each agent's capacity can be filled now or later. Because the principal cares about capacity in the aggregate but each agent cares only about his own capacity, the agents assign a higher value to the option to wait. As a result, agents sometimes withhold ideas from the principal. We show that decentralization can be a solution to this problem. Delegating assignment rights to an agent reduces the option value of waiting for the other agent sufficiently that he is willing to reveal his ideas.
